[
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention\" data-user-id=\"306459\">@Joshua Wrigley</span> and I have just put a new paper on the arXiv: <a href=\"https://arxiv.org/abs/2305.15209\">https://arxiv.org/abs/2305.15209</a></p>\n<p>This is an attempt to make the Joyal-Tierney result that <em>every topos is the topos of sheaves on a localic groupoid</em> more accessible to people who are interested in topos theory, but who are not experts. In particular, we provide an explicit description of a localic groupoid that represents the classifying topos of a given geometric theory.</p>",
        "id": 361063836,
        "sender_full_name": "Graham Manuell",
        "timestamp": 1685021838
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Nice!</p>",
        "id": 361243343,
        "sender_full_name": "Matteo Capucci (he/him)",
        "timestamp": 1685087505
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I had to remind myself this is true for Grothendieck topoi, not all elementary topoi. Am I right?</p>",
        "id": 361243651,
        "sender_full_name": "Matteo Capucci (he/him)",
        "timestamp": 1685087555
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Yes. That's right.</p>",
        "id": 361286250,
        "sender_full_name": "Graham Manuell",
        "timestamp": 1685098138
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>For example the category of finite sets is an elementary topos, but it's not equivalent to the topos of sheaves on <em>any</em> site, much less on a localic groupoid, since it's not cocomplete.</p>",
        "id": 361435860,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1685134118
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>So then here's a question, which  I posed as a reaction elsewhere to the paper coming out: is every  <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>S</mi><mi>e</mi><mi>t</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">Set</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05764em;\">S</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">e</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">t</span></span></span></span>-topos the category of (small?) sheaves on a large localic groupoid? Since locales and groupoids are dual, a large locale is merely a large frame, and is makes sense to talk about small (co)sheaves on such a thing (and then talk about coequivariant things, using a cogroupoid object).</p>",
        "id": 362347427,
        "sender_full_name": "David Michael Roberts",
        "timestamp": 1685510908
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Since left adjoints preserve colimits, any elementary topos <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"script\">E</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathcal{E}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathcal\" style=\"margin-right:0.08944em;\">E</span></span></span></span> with a geometric morphism <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>f</mi><mspace></mspace><mspace width=\"0.1111em\"/><mo lspace=\"0em\" rspace=\"0.17em\"></mo><mtext> ⁣</mtext><mo lspace=\"0em\" rspace=\"0em\">:</mo><mspace width=\"0.3333em\"/><mi mathvariant=\"script\">E</mi><mo>→</mo><mi>S</mi><mi>e</mi><mi>t</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">f\\colon \\mathcal{E} \\to Set</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8889em;vertical-align:-0.1944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10764em;\">f</span><span class=\"mspace nobreak\"></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1111em;\"></span><span class=\"mpunct\"></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:-0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mrel\">:</span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.3333em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathcal\" style=\"margin-right:0.08944em;\">E</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05764em;\">S</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">e</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">t</span></span></span></span> automatically has arbitrary small coproducts of objects in the image of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msup><mi>f</mi><mo>∗</mo></msup></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">f^*</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8889em;vertical-align:-0.1944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10764em;\">f</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.6887em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mbin mtight\">∗</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span>. I haven't thought about whether it would have arbitrary coproducts, though.</p>",
        "id": 362402818,
        "sender_full_name": "David Michael Roberts",
        "timestamp": 1685526764
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>This question is a little above my pay grade, since I'm not really a topos theorist myself and all my intuition comes from the analogy with pointfree topology. It is not even clear to me (at least without thinking about it more seriously) whether sheaves on a large frame necessarily form a topos.</p>\n<p>I know the category of uniformly continuous G-sets for a topological group G is an elementary topos that does not generally have small coproducts, but I don't know if it has a geometric morphism to Set.</p>",
        "id": 362457275,
        "sender_full_name": "Graham Manuell",
        "timestamp": 1685539668
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>You should takes small sheaves, those that are a small colimit of representables. And even then, in general it might not work. But sometimes it does!</p>",
        "id": 362462246,
        "sender_full_name": "David Michael Roberts",
        "timestamp": 1685540735
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>The result about uniformly continuous <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>G</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">G</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">G</span></span></span></span>-sets that <span class=\"user-mention\" data-user-id=\"386922\">@Graham Manuell</span>  stated comes from Example A2.1.7 in <em>Sketches of an Elephant</em>. The discrete <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>G</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">G</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">G</span></span></span></span>-sets (those for which the action is trivial) are always uniformly continuous, and the inclusion of these is left adjoint to the global sections functor. (For future readers, <a href=\"#narrow/stream/229199-learning.3A-questions/topic/Set-toposes.20are.20cocomplete.3F\">this discussion</a> is happening in parallel).</p>",
        "id": 362463417,
        "sender_full_name": "Morgan Rogers (he/him)",
        "timestamp": 1685540995
    }
]